file: crates/ctx-scan/tests/stop_hook.rs
behavior: Integration tests verifying Claude Code's Stop-hook mode is report-only: it emits a JSON systemMessage hint on stale trees, stays silent on fresh trees, and never regenerates context files itself.
edit_notes:
  - Asserts stop_hook() output is textual containing "systemMessage", "stale", and "--update"/"--update --approve" substrings; changing the hook's output format breaks these string-based checks.
  - Regeneration is exclusively ctx-run's job (post-session); these tests enforce stop_hook never calls update_run and confirm the tree remains stale after invocation.
  - Oversized-backlog test writes MAX_TARGETS+1 files to trigger the "--update --approve" hint path, coupling this test to ctx_summarize::runner::MAX_TARGETS.
  - Each test uses a fixed tmpdir name per label (not per-process-unique); concurrent runs of the same test could collide.
functions:
invariants:
  - stop_hook never changes tree freshness state (check_run().is_fresh() stays false on stale input).
  - stop_hook produces empty output when the tree is already fresh.
external_deps:
  - ctx_summarize::agent::Agent: trait implemented by StubAgent to seed a fresh tree via update_run without invoking a real LLM.